content:
This site is built using the [Quasar Framework](https://quasar.dev) and deployed as a single page application

## A bit about Quasar

The Quasar Framework is a great tool for anyone looking to make websites, mobile apps or cross platform applications quickly. The project is opensource and has been growing rapidly over the last few years and there have been some great developments. Quasar relies heavily on VueJS in order to run so in order to get started it is worth getting to grips with Vue, from then on building Webpages is fairly trivial as there is a rich set of components to choose from and deployment is also relatively straightforward.


## Pages 

Pages such as this one are written in markdown. They are then automatically bundled together with a small script, doing so keeps everything static and means no database is needed to fetch content. It also provides a simple mechanism to update site content.


The following script is used bundle the markdown files and add them to the static files directory.


```
// buildcontent.js

const fs = require("fs")
const path = require("path")

const markdown_dir = "./markdown"

const markdown_files = fs.readdirSync(markdown_dir)
const index = []
const articles = []
let filePath

markdown_files.forEach( (file, i) => {

	filePath = path.join(__dirname, markdown_dir, file); 

	let content = fs.readFileSync(filePath, {encoding: 'utf-8'})

	date = file.slice(0,8)
	file = file.replace(/\d{8}_/, "") 
	file = file.replace(/\.[^/.]+$/, "")

	// add articles to index
	index.push({
		title: file,
		id: i,
		bg: "statics/post_bg/" + date + ".jpg",
		date: {
			day: date.slice(6,8),
			month: date.slice(4,6),
			year: date.slice(0,4)
		} 
	})

	// add content 
	articles.push({
		title: file,
		content: content,
		bg: "statics/post_bg/" + date + ".jpg"
	})
})

fs.writeFileSync('./src/statics/index.json', JSON.stringify(index))
fs.writeFileSync('./src/statics/content.json', JSON.stringify(articles))
```
<br>

In order to run the script node is needed. Node is a Javascript runtime based off of Chromes V8 engine. It was created in order to run Javascript code on a local computer. Typically Javascript is only used to run webpages but with the introduction of node, javacript is being run on a local machine with access to streams such as stdin, stderr and so on. Node is typically used in conjunction with the development of webpages in order to host and serve the pages; a popular framework used to do so is Express. For my purposes I am using node in order to write the buffer to a new file know as `index.json` in turn the file is saved in the static directory of the webpage.

```
$ node buildcontent.js
```

